english:
  title: Proclamation of the Posthumous Title for Queen Gyeongshun
  author: Lee Ji-mu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King proclaims: To hold the throne with virtue and stand at the side of the sovereign requires the wisdom of worthy counsel. To grant a posthumous name and establish his memory follows the ancient rites of former kings. Thus do we compose these words to honor her memory and acclaim her virtue.

    The Late Queen of the Kim clan was born into the royal house and stood foremost among the noble families. She bore the auspicious signs of heaven's mysteries, possessed of uncommon grace. Early renowned for virtue, she came to the inner chambers as the royal consort, embodying gentle excellence and becoming the perfect match.

    When the King ascended to the throne, she rose to the Central Palace as his complement. Vigilant and diligent in her duties, her heart harbored no jealousy or private intrigues. With reverent care she conducted herself, becoming a worthy helpmate through mutual respect and duty. She cultivated the teachings of the women's quarters with such grace that her noble reputation became widespread. The kindness of the "twisted branch" extended far, and the influence of the "reeds and osprey" reached wide. She received the blessing of the Kun hexagram, and Heaven's favor manifested in the birth of the Crown Prince. Having thus secured the foundation of the realm, we believed she would long enjoy the tranquility of age.

    Yet how suddenly did affliction strike? How quickly did she depart to the grave? The white clouds carry her far away now, and her voice and visage are forever hidden from us. In sorrow we cannot but honor her memory with titles befitting her station and virtue.

    Therefore, following the established rites, we hereby dispatch commissioners to present this proclamation, granting her the posthumous title of "Gyeongshun"—the Respectful and Compliant. May her bright spirit receive this sacred honor, that her fragrant virtue endure eternally and her noble deeds shine without end.

    Alas, how great our sorrow!
  footnotes:
    - The posthumous title "Gyeongshun" (敬順) combines the virtues of reverence (敬) and compliance (順), reflecting the ideals of a Confucian queen consort.
    - References to hexagrams (Kun 坤 and Zhen 震) and classical texts (the Song of the Osprey and twisted branch imagery) invoke auspicious omens and the fulfillment of dynastic hopes through the birth of an heir.
    - The affliction of "膏肓" (ganghwang) was a metaphorical expression in East Asian medicine referring to an incurable ailment.
